05746nam a2200781Ia 9780228020257DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280202577 a10.1515/97802280202572doi  a(DE-B1597)679719  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJS1717.A2bP65 2024 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a323/.0420971223/eng/2024022600aPolitical Engagement in Canadian City Elections /ced. by R. Michael McGregor, Laura B. Stephenson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource :b35 tables, 24 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Urban Governance00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- t1 Introduction: Understanding Local Political Engagement? -- t2 Why Don’t More Immigrants Vote in Local Elections? -- t3 Economic Status and Political Engagement at the Local Level in Canada -- t4 The Impact of Ethnic, Economic and Linguistic Diversity at the Neighbourhood Level on Turnout -- t5 The School Board Archipelago: Participation in School Board Elections in Canada -- t6 Economic Voting in Canadian Municipal Elections -- t7 Who Votes for Incumbent Councillors? -- t8 The Importance of the Transportation Issue for Local Vote Choice -- t9 Political Engagement and Levels of Conceptualization: How Do Electors Think about Local Politicians? -- t10 Conclusion -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMunicipal elections in Canada don’t look much like those held at the federal and provincial levels. A key difference is a significant discrepancy in voter turnout, but relatively little is known about why far fewer people vote in city elections.Voters show less interest in local government, seeing it as less influential than other levels, yet they believe their views matter more to local politicians. Political Engagement in Canadian City Elections explores this apparent contradiction by asking who participates in politics, how they go about it, and why. Drawing from the Canadian Municipal Election Study, a novel survey of electors in eight large cities across the country in 2017 and 2018, contributors consider factors ranging from the universal – such as the demographic profile of voters or how economic conditions affect them – to the specific – for example, participation in school board and council elections.There are more municipal elections than any other kind in Canada. The discoveries in Political Engagement in Canadian City Elections collectively represent a major leap forward in our understanding of voter activity at the community and municipal level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLocal electionszCanada. 0aMunicipal governmentzCanadaxCitizen participation. 0aPolitical participationzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh  aMunicipal.  abehaviour.  acivic.  aelectorate.  alocal.  aturnout.  aurban.  avoting.1 aAnderson, Cameron D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreux, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBélanger, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouture, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaoust, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDassonneville, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErl, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLucas, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatt